</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Posttransplantation lymphoproliferative disorders (PTLDs) are a heterogeneous group of diseases that represent uncommon complications of transplantation and can lead to significant morbidity and mortality. PTLD is most prevalent during the first year following transplantation and occurs most frequently in multiorgan transplant recipients, followed by bowel, heart-lung, and lung recipients. It may involve any of the organ systems, with disease manifestation and the anatomic pattern of organ involvement being highly dependent on the type of transplantation. The current classification system includes four subtypes that have different prognoses requiring different treatment strategies. Tissue sampling is necessary for diagnosis and further subcategorization. The majority of cases are characterized by B-cell proliferation and are related to infection from Epstein-Barr virus. Knowledge of the distribution and radiologic features of PTLD allows the radiologist to play a pivotal role in making an early diagnosis and in guiding biopsy.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.294095020">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.294095020">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c01a.jpeg" height="615" width="845" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Histopathologic features of PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Hyperplastic (early) PTLD. Medium-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of benign-appearing mononuclear cells. Some retention of the underlying architecture is present, as evidenced by the residual sinusoidal space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Polymorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of mononuclear cells of varying size. “Atypical” immunoblasts (arrows) are noted adjacent to an area of confluent necrosis (lower left). <b>(c)</b> Monomorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows uniform proliferation of monoclonal B cells interrupted by macrophages with relatively clear cytoplasm, creating a “starry sky” appearance similar to that of Burkitt lymphoma. <b>(d)</b> Hodgkin-like PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows cells with features of Reed-Sternberg cells (arrows). The background mononuclear population consists of small lymphocytes and scattered other cells without the diffuse “activated” appearance of polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c01b.jpeg" height="828" width="1126" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Histopathologic features of PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Hyperplastic (early) PTLD. Medium-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of benign-appearing mononuclear cells. Some retention of the underlying architecture is present, as evidenced by the residual sinusoidal space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Polymorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of mononuclear cells of varying size. “Atypical” immunoblasts (arrows) are noted adjacent to an area of confluent necrosis (lower left). <b>(c)</b> Monomorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows uniform proliferation of monoclonal B cells interrupted by macrophages with relatively clear cytoplasm, creating a “starry sky” appearance similar to that of Burkitt lymphoma. <b>(d)</b> Hodgkin-like PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows cells with features of Reed-Sternberg cells (arrows). The background mononuclear population consists of small lymphocytes and scattered other cells without the diffuse “activated” appearance of polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c01c.jpeg" height="823" width="1126" aria-labelledby="F1C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1c.</b>  Histopathologic features of PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Hyperplastic (early) PTLD. Medium-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of benign-appearing mononuclear cells. Some retention of the underlying architecture is present, as evidenced by the residual sinusoidal space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Polymorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of mononuclear cells of varying size. “Atypical” immunoblasts (arrows) are noted adjacent to an area of confluent necrosis (lower left). <b>(c)</b> Monomorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows uniform proliferation of monoclonal B cells interrupted by macrophages with relatively clear cytoplasm, creating a “starry sky” appearance similar to that of Burkitt lymphoma. <b>(d)</b> Hodgkin-like PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows cells with features of Reed-Sternberg cells (arrows). The background mononuclear population consists of small lymphocytes and scattered other cells without the diffuse “activated” appearance of polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F1C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c01d.jpeg" height="854" width="1165" aria-labelledby="F1D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1d.</b>  Histopathologic features of PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Hyperplastic (early) PTLD. Medium-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of benign-appearing mononuclear cells. Some retention of the underlying architecture is present, as evidenced by the residual sinusoidal space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Polymorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows diffuse proliferation of mononuclear cells of varying size. “Atypical” immunoblasts (arrows) are noted adjacent to an area of confluent necrosis (lower left). <b>(c)</b> Monomorphic PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows uniform proliferation of monoclonal B cells interrupted by macrophages with relatively clear cytoplasm, creating a “starry sky” appearance similar to that of Burkitt lymphoma. <b>(d)</b> Hodgkin-like PTLD. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; hematoxylineosin stain) shows cells with features of Reed-Sternberg cells (arrows). The background mononuclear population consists of small lymphocytes and scattered other cells without the diffuse “activated” appearance of polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F1D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g02a.jpeg" height="1330" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 15 years earlier. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show dilatation and wall thickening of the small bowel (* in <b>a</b>), with marked FDG uptake on the PET/CT image. The results of biopsy of a concurrent renal lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c02b.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 15 years earlier. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show dilatation and wall thickening of the small bowel (* in <b>a</b>), with marked FDG uptake on the PET/CT image. The results of biopsy of a concurrent renal lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g03a.jpeg" height="1376" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 42-year-old man with a history of total colectomy for inflammatory bowel disease. The patient had undergone liver transplantation 12 years earlier. Arrow indicates the surgical sutures from an ileorectal anastomosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilatation and wall thickening of the J pouch (*). <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment PET/CT image reveals significant improvement in the condition of the J pouch. The results of biopsy of the J pouch were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c03b.jpeg" height="959" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 42-year-old man with a history of total colectomy for inflammatory bowel disease. The patient had undergone liver transplantation 12 years earlier. Arrow indicates the surgical sutures from an ileorectal anastomosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilatation and wall thickening of the J pouch (*). <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment PET/CT image reveals significant improvement in the condition of the J pouch. The results of biopsy of the J pouch were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g04a.jpeg" height="1313" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 30-year-old man who had undergone small bowel transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan reveals an extranodal mass (*) engulfing loops of a small bowel allograft. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the surgically resected specimen shows the mass engulfing bowel loops. Findings at histologic examination of the allograft were consistent with polymorphic PTLD. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c04b.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 30-year-old man who had undergone small bowel transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan reveals an extranodal mass (*) engulfing loops of a small bowel allograft. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the surgically resected specimen shows the mass engulfing bowel loops. Findings at histologic examination of the allograft were consistent with polymorphic PTLD. Scale is in centimeters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g05a.jpeg" height="1156" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 9 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study shows multiple target lesions (arrows) in the stomach and small bowel. <b>(b)</b> Gastroduodenal endoscopic image shows raised ulcerative lesions with surrounding edema. The results of biopsy of a duodenal lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c05b.jpeg" height="1049" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 9 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Image from a small bowel follow-through study shows multiple target lesions (arrows) in the stomach and small bowel. <b>(b)</b> Gastroduodenal endoscopic image shows raised ulcerative lesions with surrounding edema. The results of biopsy of a duodenal lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g06x.jpeg" height="1348" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 13-year-old girl who presented with bowel obstruction 1 year after undergoing liver transplantation. Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a small bowel intussusception, with orally administered contrast material within the thick-walled proximal jejunal intussusceptum (black arrow) and intussuscipiens (white arrow). Monomorphic PTLD was confirmed with endoscopic biopsy of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g07x.jpeg" height="1295" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 66-year-old man who had undergone heart transplantation 10 years earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a large, necrotic exophytic mass (*) arising from the second portion of the duodenum (arrow). The results of biopsy of the mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g08a.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 57-year-old woman who had undergone renal transplantation 14 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show enteric contrast material within a circumferentially thickened cecum (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a pericecal mesenteric (* in <b>a</b>) and retroperitoneal nodal mass with increased FDG uptake. <b>(c)</b> Axial posttreatment fused PET/CT image shows marked improvement of the lesion. The results of biopsy of the mesenteric nodal mass were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c08b.jpeg" height="971" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 57-year-old woman who had undergone renal transplantation 14 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show enteric contrast material within a circumferentially thickened cecum (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a pericecal mesenteric (* in <b>a</b>) and retroperitoneal nodal mass with increased FDG uptake. <b>(c)</b> Axial posttreatment fused PET/CT image shows marked improvement of the lesion. The results of biopsy of the mesenteric nodal mass were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c08c.jpeg" height="958" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 57-year-old woman who had undergone renal transplantation 14 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show enteric contrast material within a circumferentially thickened cecum (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a pericecal mesenteric (* in <b>a</b>) and retroperitoneal nodal mass with increased FDG uptake. <b>(c)</b> Axial posttreatment fused PET/CT image shows marked improvement of the lesion. The results of biopsy of the mesenteric nodal mass were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g09x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 71-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 12 years earlier. Axial unenhanced CT scan shows marked thickening of the appendix (*). The results of endoscopic biopsy of the lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g10x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 79-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 12 years earlier. Unenhanced CT scan shows extensive circumferential thickening of the gastric antrum (arrows). The results of endoscopic biopsy of the lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g11a.jpeg" height="1326" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 21-year-old woman who had undergone heart transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows low-attenuation lesions (black arrows) and an enlarged, low-attenuation porta hepatis node (white arrow). The results of biopsy of an enlarged mediastinal lymph node were consistent with polymorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment contrast-enhanced CT scan shows marked resolution of the majority of the hepatic lesions (black arrow) and a decrease in the size of the porta hepatis node (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g11b.jpeg" height="1318" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 21-year-old woman who had undergone heart transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows low-attenuation lesions (black arrows) and an enlarged, low-attenuation porta hepatis node (white arrow). The results of biopsy of an enlarged mediastinal lymph node were consistent with polymorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment contrast-enhanced CT scan shows marked resolution of the majority of the hepatic lesions (black arrow) and a decrease in the size of the porta hepatis node (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g12x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in the same patient as in <a href="#F6">Figure 6</a>. Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image of the liver shows an echogenic lesion with a hypoechoic rim (arrow). The results of US-guided needle biopsy of the lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g13x.jpeg" height="1248" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 59-year-old woman who had undergone lung transplantation 2 years earlier. Axial unenhanced CT scan shows multifocal and infiltrative disease in the liver. The results of US-guided biopsy of the lesions were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g14x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in the same patient as in <a href="#F11A">Figure 11</a>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan reveals multiple low-attenuation lesions in the spleen. The results of biopsy of a hepatic lesion were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g15a.jpeg" height="1737" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 29-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 10 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows innumerable hypovascular lesions in the renal allograft. Note the enlarged nodal mass in the left lower quadrant (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows the renal lesions and the nodal mass (arrow), which is hypointense. The results of biopsy of the mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g15b.jpeg" height="1739" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 29-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 10 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows innumerable hypovascular lesions in the renal allograft. Note the enlarged nodal mass in the left lower quadrant (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows the renal lesions and the nodal mass (arrow), which is hypointense. The results of biopsy of the mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g16a.jpeg" height="1664" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in the same patient as in <a href="#F2A">Figure 2</a>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image reveals a mass arising from the upper pole of the left kidney (white arrow) and a perinephric lymph node (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesions (arrows) to be hypovascular. The results of biopsy of the renal mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows increased FDG uptake in all lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g16b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1758" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in the same patient as in <a href="#F2A">Figure 2</a>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image reveals a mass arising from the upper pole of the left kidney (white arrow) and a perinephric lymph node (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesions (arrows) to be hypovascular. The results of biopsy of the renal mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows increased FDG uptake in all lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c16c.jpeg" height="1243" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F16C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16c.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in the same patient as in <a href="#F2A">Figure 2</a>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image reveals a mass arising from the upper pole of the left kidney (white arrow) and a perinephric lymph node (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows the lesions (arrows) to be hypovascular. The results of biopsy of the renal mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(c)</b> Coronal fused PET/CT image shows increased FDG uptake in all lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F16C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g17a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 23-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 4 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial out-of-phase MR image shows bilateral adrenal infiltration (arrows) without signal loss, a finding that indicates nonadenomatous lesions. The results of biopsy of a mesenteric node were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment fused PET/CT image shows resolution of the lesions, with no FDG uptake in the adrenal glands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F17A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g17b.jpeg" height="1348" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 23-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 4 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial out-of-phase MR image shows bilateral adrenal infiltration (arrows) without signal loss, a finding that indicates nonadenomatous lesions. The results of biopsy of a mesenteric node were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment fused PET/CT image shows resolution of the lesions, with no FDG uptake in the adrenal glands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F17B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g18a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old woman who had undergone renal transplantation 9 years earlier. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show a left adrenal mass (arrow in <b>a</b>) with increased FDG uptake. The results of biopsy of a duodenal lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c18b.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old woman who had undergone renal transplantation 9 years earlier. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> show a left adrenal mass (arrow in <b>a</b>) with increased FDG uptake. The results of biopsy of a duodenal lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g19x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 19-year-old woman who had undergone multivisceral transplantation 7 months earlier. Axial CT scan shows a mesenteric lymph node (*). Results of CT-guided biopsy confirmed the diagnosis of monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c20x.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 60-year-old man who had undergone renal transplantation 21 years earlier. Axial fused PET/CT image shows extensive retroperitoneal lymph node enlargement with increased FDG uptake. The results of biopsy were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g21a.jpeg" height="1214" width="1620" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old woman who had undergone renal and pancreatic transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows numerous lung nodules. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows increased FDG uptake (arrow). The results of biopsy of a hepatic lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c21b.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 48-year-old woman who had undergone renal and pancreatic transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows numerous lung nodules. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows increased FDG uptake (arrow). The results of biopsy of a hepatic lesion were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g22a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22a.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 21-year-old woman who had undergone heart transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows hilar and mediastinal adenopathy (arrows) and bilateral pleural effusions. The results of biopsy of a hepatic lesion were consistent with polymorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a marked decrease in node size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F22A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g22b.jpeg" height="1348" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22b.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 21-year-old woman who had undergone heart transplantation 5 months earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows hilar and mediastinal adenopathy (arrows) and bilateral pleural effusions. The results of biopsy of a hepatic lesion were consistent with polymorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial posttreatment contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a marked decrease in node size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F22B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g23x.jpeg" height="1146" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 14-year-old boy who had undergone heart-lung transplantation 6 years earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan reveals right middle lobe consolidation (arrow). The results of transbronchial biopsy were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g24x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24.</b>  Polymorphic PTLD in a 54-year-old woman who had undergone liver transplantation 4 months earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a soft-tissue mass (*) with extrapleural invasion. The results of biopsy of a pharyngeal lesion were consistent with polymorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g25a.jpeg" height="1576" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F25A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 61-year-old woman who had undergone liver transplantation 3 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows a hyperattenuating mass (arrow) in the left cerebellar hemisphere abutting the vermis, along with surrounding edema. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fluid-attenuated inversion recovery T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is hypointense. There is also markedly hyperintense vasogenic edema surrounding the mass. <b>(c)</b> On an axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, the mass shows mild enhancement (arrow). The results of endoscopic biopsy of the small bowel were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F25A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g25b.jpeg" height="1578" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F25B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 61-year-old woman who had undergone liver transplantation 3 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows a hyperattenuating mass (arrow) in the left cerebellar hemisphere abutting the vermis, along with surrounding edema. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fluid-attenuated inversion recovery T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is hypointense. There is also markedly hyperintense vasogenic edema surrounding the mass. <b>(c)</b> On an axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, the mass shows mild enhancement (arrow). The results of endoscopic biopsy of the small bowel were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F25B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g25c.jpeg" height="1584" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F25C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25c.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 61-year-old woman who had undergone liver transplantation 3 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows a hyperattenuating mass (arrow) in the left cerebellar hemisphere abutting the vermis, along with surrounding edema. <b>(b)</b> On an axial fluid-attenuated inversion recovery T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is hypointense. There is also markedly hyperintense vasogenic edema surrounding the mass. <b>(c)</b> On an axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, the mass shows mild enhancement (arrow). The results of endoscopic biopsy of the small bowel were consistent with monomorphic PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F25C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29g26a.jpeg" height="1522" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F26A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26a.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 35-year-old man who had undergone heart transplantation 9 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass (arrow) in the adductor compartment of the thigh. The results of biopsy of the mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image reveals intense FDG uptake in the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F26A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294095020/asset/images/g09jl29c26b.jpeg" height="1193" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F26B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26b.</b>  Monomorphic PTLD in a 35-year-old man who had undergone heart transplantation 9 years earlier. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass (arrow) in the adductor compartment of the thigh. The results of biopsy of the mass were consistent with monomorphic PTLD. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image reveals intense FDG uptake in the mass (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294095020&amp;id=F26B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Hislop</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">AD</span></span>, Taylor GS, Sauce D, Rickinson AB. Cellular responses to viral infection in humans: lessons from Epstein-Barr virus. <em>Annu Rev Immunol</em>2007; 25: 587–617.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev.immunol.25.022106.141553">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17378764/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Annu+Rev+Immunol&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;pages=587&am